# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tensor-processing-unit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] NPU can be standalone, a part of a CPU or a part of a GPU.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Their purpose is either to efficiently execute already trained AI models (inference) or to train AI models.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] NPUs can be more efficient in terms of speed or power consumption.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] NPU applications include algorithms for robotics, Internet of things, and data-intensive or sensor-driven tasks.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] They are often manycore or spatial designs and focus on low-precision arithmetic, novel dataflow architectures, or in-memory computing capability.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] As of 2024, a widely used datacenter-grade AI integrated circuit chip, the Nvidia H100 GPU, contains tens of billions of MOSFETs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] AI accelerators are used in Apple silicon, Qualcomm, Samsung, Huawei, and Google Tensor smartphone processors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Vision processing units are accelerators specialized for machine vision algorithms such as CNN (convolutional neural networks) and SIFT (scale-invariant feature transform).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] They are used in devices that need to keep track of objects visually such as AR headsets and drones.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] It is more recently (circa 2017) added to processors from Apple and (circa 2022) to processors from Intel and AMD.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] All models of Intel Meteor Lake processors have a built-in *versatile processor unit* (*VPU*) for accelerating inference for computer vision and deep learning.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] On consumer devices, the NPU is intended to be small, power-efficient, but reasonably fast when used to run small models.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] To do this they are designed to support low-bitwidth operations using data types such as INT4, INT8, FP8, and FP16.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] A common metric is trillions of operations per second (TOPS).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Although TOPS does not explicitly specify the kind of operations, it is typically INT8 additions and multiplications.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Accelerators are used in cloud computing servers: e.g., tensor processing units (TPU) for Google Cloud Platform, and Trainium and Inferentia chips for Amazon Web Services.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Many vendor-specific terms exist for devices in this category, and it is an emerging technology without a dominant design.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Since the late 2010s, graphics processing units designed by companies such as Nvidia and AMD often include AI-specific hardware in the form of dedicated functional units for low-precision matrix-multiplication operations.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] These GPUs are commonly used as AI accelerators, both for training and inference.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Although NPUs are tailored for low-precision (e.g., FP16, INT8) matrix multiplication operations, they can be used to emulate higher-precision matrix multiplications in scientific computing.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] As modern GPUs place much focus on making the NPU part fast, using emulated FP64 (Ozaki scheme) on NPUs can potentially outperform native FP64.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] This has been demonstrated using FP16-emulated FP64 on NVIDIA TITAN RTX and using INT8-emulated FP64 on NVIDIA consumer GPUs and the A100 GPU.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Consumer GPUs especially benefited as they have limited FP64 hardware capacity, showing a 6× speedup.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Since CUDA Toolkit 13.0 Update 2, cuBLAS automatically uses INT8-emulated FP64 matrix multiplication of the equivalent precision if it is faster than native.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] This is in addition to the FP16-emulated FP32 feature introduced in version 12.9.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] An operating system or a higher-level library may provide application programming interfaces such as TensorFlow with LiteRT Next (Android), CoreML (iOS, macOS) or DirectML (Windows).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Formats such as ONNX are used to represent trained neural networks.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Consumer CPU-integrated NPUs are accessible through vendor-specific APIs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] AMD (Ryzen AI), Intel (OpenVINO), Apple silicon (CoreML), and Qualcomm (SNPE) each have their own APIs, which can be built upon by a higher-level library.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] GPUs generally use existing GPGPU pipelines such as CUDA and OpenCL adapted for lower precisions and specialized matrix-multiplication operations.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Custom-built systems such as the Google TPU use private interfaces.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] There are a large number of separate underlying acceleration APIs and compilers/runtimes in use in the AI field, causing a great increase in software development effort due to the many combinations involved.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] As of 2025, the open standard organization Khronos Group is pursuing standardization of AI-related interfaces to reduce the amount of work needed.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/ai-accelerator] Khronos is working on three separate fronts: expansion of data types and intrinsic operations in OpenCL and Vulkan, inclusion of compute graphs in SPIR-V, and a NNEF/SkriptND file format for describing a neural network.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] To perform computing tasks more efficiently, generally one can invest time and money in improving the software, improving the hardware, or both.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] There are various approaches with advantages and disadvantages in terms of decreased latency, increased throughput, and reduced energy consumption.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Typical advantages of focusing on software may include greater versatility, more rapid development, lower non-recurring engineering costs, heightened portability, and ease of updating features or patching bugs, at the cost of overhead to compute general operations.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] This hierarchy includes general-purpose processors such as CPUs, more specialized processors such as programmable shaders in a GPU, applications implemented on field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs), and fixed-function implemented on application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Hardware acceleration is advantageous for performance, and practical when the functions are fixed, so updates are not as needed as in software solutions.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] With the advent of reprogrammable logic devices such as FPGAs, the restriction of hardware acceleration to fully fixed algorithms has eased since 2010, allowing hardware acceleration to be applied to problem domains requiring modification to algorithms and processing control flow.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] The disadvantage, however, is that in many open source projects, it requires proprietary libraries that not all vendors are keen to distribute or expose, making it difficult to integrate in such projects.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Integrated circuits are designed to handle various operations on both analog and digital signals.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] In computing, digital signals are the most common and are typically represented as binary numbers.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Computer hardware and software use this binary representation to perform computations.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] This is done by processing Boolean functions on the binary input, and then outputting the results for storage or further processing by other devices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Because all Turing machines can run any computable function, it is always possible to design custom hardware that performs the same function as a given piece of software.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Conversely, software can always be used to emulate the function of a given piece of hardware.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Custom hardware may offer higher performance per watt for the same functions that can be specified in software.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Hardware description languages (HDLs) such as Verilog and VHDL can model the same semantics as software and synthesize the design into a netlist that can be programmed to an FPGA or composed into the logic gates of an ASIC.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] The vast majority of software-based computing occurs on machines implementing the von Neumann architecture, collectively known as stored-program computers.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Computer programs are stored as data and executed by processors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Such processors must fetch and decode instructions, as well as load data operands from memory (as part of the instruction cycle), to execute the instructions constituting the software program.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Relying on a common cache for code and data leads to the "von Neumann bottleneck", a fundamental limitation on the throughput of software on processors implementing the von Neumann architecture.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Even in the modified Harvard architecture, where instructions and data have separate caches in the memory hierarchy, there is overhead to decoding instruction opcodes and multiplexing available execution units on a microprocessor or microcontroller, leading to low circuit utilization.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Modern processors that provide simultaneous multithreading exploit under-utilization of available processor functional units and instruction level parallelism between different hardware threads.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Hardware execution units do not in general rely on the von Neumann or modified Harvard architectures and do not need to perform the instruction fetch and decode steps of an instruction cycle and incur those stages' overhead.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] If needed calculations are specified in a register transfer level (RTL) hardware design, the time and circuit area costs that would be incurred by instruction fetch and decoding stages can be reclaimed and put to other uses.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] This reclamation saves time, power, and circuit area in computation.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] The reclaimed resources can be used for increased parallel computation, other functions, communication, or memory, as well as increased input/output capabilities.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] This comes at the cost of general-purpose utility.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Custom hardware is limited in parallel processing capability only by the area and logic blocks available on the integrated circuit die.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Therefore, hardware is much freer to offer massive parallelism than software on general-purpose processors, offering a possibility of implementing the parallel random-access machine (PRAM) model.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] It is common to build multicore and manycore processing units out of microprocessor IP core schematics on a single FPGA or ASIC.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Similarly, specialized functional units can be composed in parallel, as in digital signal processing, without being embedded in a processor IP core.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Therefore, hardware acceleration is often employed for repetitive, fixed tasks involving little conditional branching, especially on large amounts of data.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] This is how Nvidia's CUDA line of GPUs are implemented.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] As device mobility has increased, new metrics have been developed that measure the relative performance of specific acceleration protocols, considering characteristics such as physical hardware dimensions, power consumption, and operations throughput.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] These can be summarized into three categories: task efficiency, implementation efficiency, and flexibility.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Appropriate metrics consider the area of the hardware along with both the corresponding operations throughput and energy consumed.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] The hardware that performs the acceleration may be part of a general-purpose CPU, or a separate unit called a hardware accelerator, though they are usually referred to with a more specific term, such as 3D accelerator, or cryptographic accelerator.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Traditionally, processors were sequential (instructions are executed one by one), and were designed to run general-purpose algorithms controlled by instruction fetch (for example, moving temporary results to and from a register file).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Hardware accelerators improve the execution of a specific algorithm by allowing greater concurrency, having specific datapaths for their temporary variables, and reducing the overhead of instruction control in the fetch-decode-execute cycle.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Modern processors are multi-core and often feature parallel "single-instruction; multiple data" (SIMD) units.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Such units can be integrated withint the CPU or offered by additional components as the AMD AI engines.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Even so, hardware acceleration still yields benefits.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Hardware acceleration is suitable for any computation-intensive algorithm that is executed frequently in a task or program.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/hardware-acceleration] Depending upon the granularity, hardware acceleration can vary from a small functional unit to a large functional block (like motion estimation in MPEG-2).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] In mathematics, specifically in linear algebra, **matrix multiplication** is a binary operation that produces a matrix from two matrices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] For matrix multiplication, the number of columns in the first matrix must be equal to the number of rows in the second matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The resulting matrix, known as the **matrix product**, has the number of rows of the first and the number of columns of the second matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The product of matrices **A** and **B** is denoted as **AB**.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Matrix multiplication was first described by the French mathematician Jacques Philippe Marie Binet in 1812, to represent the composition of linear maps that are represented by matrices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Matrix multiplication is thus a basic tool of linear algebra, and as such has numerous applications in many areas of mathematics, as well as in applied mathematics, statistics, physics, economics, and engineering.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Computing matrix products is a central operation in all computational applications of linear algebra.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This article will use the following notational conventions: matrices are represented by capital letters in bold, e.g.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] **a**; and entries of vectors and matrices are italic (they are numbers from a field), e.g.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Index notation is often the clearest way to express definitions, and is used as standard in the literature.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The entry in row i, column j of matrix **A** is indicated by (**A**)*ij*, *A**ij* or *a**ij*.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] **A**1, **A**2, is used to select a matrix (not a matrix entry) from a collection of matrices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] That is, the entry ⁠ $c_{ij}$ ⁠ of the product is obtained by multiplying term-by-term the entries of the ith row of **A** and the jth column of **B**, and summing these n products.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] In other words, ⁠ $c_{ij}$ ⁠ is the dot product of the ith row of **A** and the jth column of **B**.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Thus the product **AB** is defined if and only if the number of columns in **A** equals the number of rows in **B**, in this case *n*.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] In most scenarios, the entries are numbers, but they may be any kind of mathematical objects for which an addition and a multiplication are defined, that are associative, and such that the addition is commutative, and the multiplication is distributive with respect to the addition.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] In particular, the entries may be matrices themselves (see block matrix).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] One way of looking at this is that the changes from "plain" vector to column vector and back are assumed and left implicit.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Similarly, a vector $\mathbf {x}$ of length n can be viewed as a row vector, corresponding to a $1\times n$ matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] A vector with n components can be represented as a *1* × *n* matrix (a row-vector) or as a *n* × *1* matrix (a column-vector).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The matrix multiplication between the column-vector $\mathbf {a}$ and the row-vector $\mathbf {b} ^{\mathrm {T} }$ , also known as outer-product $\mathbf {a} \mathbf {b} ^{\mathrm {T} }$ , will, instead, give a *n* × *n* matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Historically, matrix multiplication has been introduced for facilitating and clarifying computations in linear algebra.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This strong relationship between matrix multiplication and linear algebra remains fundamental in all mathematics, as well as in physics, chemistry, engineering and computer science.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If a vector space has a finite basis, its vectors are each uniquely represented by a finite sequence of scalars, called a coordinate vector, whose elements are the coordinates of the vector on the basis.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] These coordinate vectors form another vector space, which is isomorphic to the original vector space.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] A coordinate vector is commonly organized as a column matrix (also called a *column vector*), which is a matrix with only one column.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] So, a column vector represents both a coordinate vector, and a vector of the original vector space.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Using a Cartesian coordinate system in a Euclidean plane, the rotation by an angle $\alpha$ around the origin is a linear map.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] More precisely, ${\begin{bmatrix}x'\\y'\end{bmatrix}}={\begin{bmatrix}\cos \alpha &-\sin \alpha \\\sin \alpha &\cos \alpha \end{bmatrix}}{\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix}},$ where the source point $(x,y)$ and its image $(x',y')$ are written as column vectors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] That is, the composition corresponds to the rotation by angle $\alpha +\beta$ , as expected.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] As an example, a fictitious factory uses 4 kinds of basic commodities, $b_{1},b_{2},b_{3},b_{4}$ to produce 3 kinds of intermediate goods, $m_{1},m_{2},m_{3}$ , which in turn are used to produce 3 kinds of final products, $f_{1},f_{2},f_{3}$ .
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] provide the amount of basic commodities needed for a given amount of intermediate goods, and the amount of intermediate goods needed for a given amount of final products, respectively.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] For example, to produce one unit of intermediate good $m_{1}$ , one unit of basic commodity $b_{1}$ , two units of $b_{2}$ , no units of $b_{3}$ , and one unit of $b_{4}$ are needed, corresponding to the first column of $\mathbf {A}$ .
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] this matrix directly provides the amounts of basic commodities needed for given amounts of final goods.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] For example, the bottom left entry of $\mathbf {AB}$ is computed as $1\cdot 1+1\cdot 2+2\cdot 4=11$ , reflecting that $11$ units of $b_{4}$ are needed to produce one unit of $f_{1}$ .
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Indeed, one $b_{4}$ unit is needed for $m_{1}$ , one for each of two $m_{2}$ , and 2 for each of the four $m_{3}$ units that go into the $f_{1}$ unit, see picture.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Similarly, the product matrix $\mathbf {AB}$ can be used to compute the needed amounts of basic goods for other final-good amount data.
