[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] where $\mathbf {x} ^{\dagger }$ denotes the conjugate transpose of $\mathbf {x}$ (conjugate of the transpose, or equivalently transpose of the conjugate).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Matrix multiplication shares some properties with usual multiplication.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] However, matrix multiplication is not defined if the number of columns of the first factor differs from the number of rows of the second factor, and it is non-commutative, even when the product remains defined after changing the order of the factors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If **A** and **B** are matrices of respective sizes ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ and ⁠ $p\times q$ ⁠, then $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {B}$ is defined if ⁠ $n=p$ ⁠, and $\mathbf {B} \mathbf {A}$ is defined if ⁠ $m=q$ ⁠.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Therefore, if one of the products is defined, the other one need not be defined.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If ⁠ $m=q\neq n=p$ ⁠, the two products are defined, but have different sizes; thus they cannot be equal.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Only if ⁠ $m=q=n=p$ ⁠, that is, if **A** and **B** are square matrices of the same size, are both products defined and of the same size.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If, instead of a field, the entries are supposed to belong to a ring, then one must add the condition that c belongs to the center of the ring.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] One special case where commutativity does occur is when **D** and **E** are two (square) diagonal matrices (of the same size); then **DE** = **ED**.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Again, if the matrices are over a general ring rather than a field, the corresponding entries in each must also commute with each other for this to hold.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The matrix product is distributive with respect to matrix addition.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If **A** is a matrix and c a scalar, then the matrices $c\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {A} c$ are obtained by left or right multiplying all entries of **A** by c.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If the scalars have the commutative property, then all four matrices are equal.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] More generally, all four are equal if *c* belongs to the center of a ring containing the entries of the matrices, because in this case, *c***X** = **X***c* for all matrices **X**.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If the scalars have the commutative property, the transpose of a product of matrices is the product, in the reverse order, of the transposes of the factors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] where T denotes the transpose, that is the interchange of rows and columns.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This identity does not hold for noncommutative entries, since the order between the entries of **A** and **B** is reversed, when one expands the definition of the matrix product.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] where * denotes the entry-wise complex conjugate of a matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This results from applying to the definition of matrix product the fact that the conjugate of a sum is the sum of the conjugates of the summands and the conjugate of a product is the product of the conjugates of the factors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Transposition acts on the indices of the entries, while conjugation acts independently on the entries themselves.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] where † denotes the conjugate transpose (conjugate of the transpose, or equivalently transpose of the conjugate).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This extends naturally to the product of any number of matrices provided that the dimensions match.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] is defined and does not depend on the order of the multiplications, if the order of the matrices is kept fixed.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] These properties may be proved by straightforward but complicated summation manipulations.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This result also follows from the fact that matrices represent linear maps.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Therefore, the associative property of matrices is simply a specific case of the associative property of function composition.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Although the result of a sequence of matrix products does not depend on the order of operation (provided that the order of the matrices is not changed), the computational complexity may depend dramatically on this order.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Algorithms have been designed for choosing the best order of products; see Matrix chain multiplication.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Let us denote ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ the set of *n*×*n* square matrices with entries in a ring R, which, in practice, is often a field.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] In ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ , the product is defined for every pair of matrices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This makes ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ a ring, which has the identity matrix **I** as an identity element (the matrix whose diagonal entries are equal to 1 and all other entries are 0).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This ring is also an associative R-algebra.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] If *n* > 1, many matrices do not have a multiplicative inverse.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] For example, a matrix such that all entries of a row (or a column) are 0 does not have an inverse.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] A matrix that has an inverse is an invertible matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] A product of matrices is invertible if and only if each factor is invertible.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] When R is commutative, and, in particular, when it is a field, the determinant of a product is the product of the determinants.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The other matrix invariants do not behave as well with products.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Nevertheless, if R is commutative, **AB** and **BA** have the same trace, the same characteristic polynomial, and the same eigenvalues with the same multiplicities.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] However, the eigenvectors are generally different if **AB** ≠ **BA**.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] One may raise a square matrix to any nonnegative integer power multiplying it by itself repeatedly in the same way as for ordinary numbers.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Computing the kth power of a matrix needs *k* – 1 times the time of a single matrix multiplication, if it is done with the trivial algorithm (repeated multiplication).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] As this may be very time consuming, one generally prefers using exponentiation by squaring, which requires less than 2 log2 *k* matrix multiplications, and is therefore much more efficient.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] An easy case for exponentiation is that of a diagonal matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The definition of matrix product requires that the entries belong to a semiring, and does not require multiplication of elements of the semiring to be commutative.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] In many applications, the matrix elements belong to a field, although the tropical semiring is also a common choice for graph shortest path problems.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Even in the case of matrices over fields, the product is not commutative in general, although it is associative and is distributive over matrix addition.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The identity matrices (which are the square matrices whose entries are zero outside of the main diagonal and 1 on the main diagonal) are identity elements of the matrix product.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] It follows that the *n* × *n* matrices over a ring form a ring, which is noncommutative except if *n* = 1 and the ground ring is commutative.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] A square matrix may have a multiplicative inverse, called an inverse matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] In the common case where the entries belong to a commutative ring R, a matrix has an inverse if and only if its determinant has a multiplicative inverse in R.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The determinant of a product of square matrices is the product of the determinants of the factors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The *n* × *n* matrices that have an inverse form a group under matrix multiplication, the subgroups of which are called matrix groups.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Many classical groups (including all finite groups) are isomorphic to matrix groups; this is the starting point of the theory of group representations.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Matrices are the morphisms of a category, the category of matrices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The objects are the natural numbers that measure the size of matrices, and the composition of morphisms is matrix multiplication.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The source of a morphism is the number of columns of the corresponding matrix, and the target is the number of rows.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] The matrix multiplication algorithm that results from the definition requires, in the worst case, ⁠ $n^{3}$ ⁠ multiplications and ⁠ $(n-1)n^{2}$ ⁠ additions of scalars to compute the product of two square *n*×*n* matrices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Its computational complexity is therefore ⁠ $O(n^{3})$ ⁠, in a model of computation for which the scalar operations take constant time.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] Rather surprisingly, this complexity is not optimal, as shown in 1969 by Volker Strassen, who provided an algorithm, now called Strassen's algorithm, with a complexity of $O(n^{\log _{2}7})\approx O(n^{2.8074}).$ Strassen's algorithm can be parallelized to further improve the performance.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] As of January 2024, the best peer-reviewed matrix multiplication algorithm is by Virginia Vassilevska Williams, Yinzhan Xu, Zixuan Xu, and Renfei Zhou and has complexity *O*(*n*2.371552).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] It is not known whether matrix multiplication can be performed in *n*2 + o(1) time.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/matrix-multiplication] This would be optimal, since one must read the ⁠ $n^{2}$ ⁠ elements of a matrix in order to multiply it with another matrix.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] In computing, especially digital signal processing, the **multiply–accumulate** (**MAC**) or **multiply–add** (**MAD**) operation is a common step that computes the product of two numbers and adds that product to an accumulator.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The hardware unit that performs the operation is known as a **multiplier–accumulator** (**MAC unit**); the operation itself is also often called a MAC or a MAD operation.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] When done with floating-point numbers, it might be performed with two roundings (typical in many DSPs), or with a single rounding.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] When performed with a single rounding, it is called a **fused multiply–add** (**FMA**) or **fused multiply–accumulate** (**FMAC**).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] Modern computers may contain a dedicated MAC, consisting of a multiplier implemented in combinational logic followed by an adder and an accumulator register that stores the result.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The output of the register is fed back to one input of the adder, so that on each clock cycle, the output of the multiplier is added to the register.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] Combinational multipliers require a large amount of logic, but can compute a product much more quickly than the method of shifting and adding typical of earlier computers.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] Percy Ludgate was the first to conceive a MAC in his Analytical Machine of 1909, and the first to exploit a MAC for division (using multiplication seeded by reciprocal, via the convergent series (1+*x*)−1).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The first modern processors to be equipped with MAC units were digital signal processors, but the technique is now also common in general-purpose processors.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] When done with integers, the operation is typically exact (computed modulo some power of two).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] However, floating-point numbers have only a certain amount of mathematical precision.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] That is, digital floating-point arithmetic is generally not associative or distributive.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] (See Floating-point arithmetic § Accuracy problems.) Therefore, it makes a difference to the result whether the multiply–add is performed with two roundings, or in one operation with a single rounding (a fused multiply–add).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] IEEE 754-2008 specifies that it must be performed with one rounding, yielding a more accurate result.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] A **fused multiply–add** (**FMA** or **fmadd**) is a floating-point multiply–add operation performed in one step (fused operation), with a single rounding.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] Fused multiply–add can usually be relied on to give more accurate results.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] However, William Kahan has pointed out that it can give problems if used unthinkingly.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] This could then lead to an error if, for instance, the square root of the result is then evaluated.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] When implemented inside a microprocessor, an FMA can be faster than a multiply operation followed by an add.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] However, standard industrial implementations based on the original IBM RS/6000 design require a 2*N*-bit adder to compute the sum properly.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] Another benefit of including this instruction is that it allows an efficient software implementation of division (see division algorithm) and square root (see methods of computing square roots) operations, thus eliminating the need for dedicated hardware for those operations.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] Some machines combine multiple fused multiply add operations into a single step, e.g. performing a four-element dot-product on two 128-bit SIMD registers `a0×b0 + a1×b1 + a2×b2 + a3×b3` with single cycle throughput.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The FMA operation is included in IEEE 754-2008.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The GCC and Clang C compilers do such transformations by default for processor architectures that support FMA instructions.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] With GCC, which does not support the aforementioned pragma, this can be globally controlled by the `-ffp-contract` command line option.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] A simpler implementation of MADD involves truncating the result of the multiplication before adding.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] This provides no accuracy benefit (and in fact is less accurate), but was, before 2010, more commonly supported on GPUs than the precise FMA.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] An example is seen in the "FMAD" instruction of Nvidia PTX.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The OpenCL optimization option `-cl-mad-enable` enables replacing `a * b + c` with `mad(a, b, c)`, the function computing the equivalent expression "with reduced accuracy" in OpenCL 1.0.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The accuracy of this option as well as `mad()` has become more nuanced in newer versions of OpenCL, only allowing reduced accuracy in the "embedded profile" as of version 3.0.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] The Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) VAX's `POLY` instruction is used for evaluating polynomials with Horner's rule using a succession of multiply and add steps.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] Instruction descriptions do not specify whether the multiply and add are performed using a single FMA step.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] This instruction has been a part of the VAX instruction set since its original 11/780 implementation in 1977.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] According to Bob Supnik, the machine internally performs the multiplication and addition in extended precision, then converts to the target format.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] There is therefore a rounding step after multiplication.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] As a result, although this operation is more precise than a naive `a * b + c` in target format, it does not meet the IEEE definition of FMA.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/multiply-accumulate-operation] This behavior is also comparable to using `FLT_EVAL_METHOD == 2` on x87.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] In parallel computer architectures, a **systolic array** is a homogeneous network of tightly coupled data processing units (DPUs) called cells or nodes.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Each node or DPU independently computes a partial result as a function of the data received from its upstream neighbours, stores the result within itself and passes it downstream.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The principles of systolic-like data flow were first seen in Colossus, which was an early computer used to break German Lorenz ciphers during World War II.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Due to the classified nature of Colossus, they were independently invented by H.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Kung and Charles Leiserson who described arrays for many dense linear algebra computations (matrix product, solving systems of linear equations, LU decomposition, etc.) for banded matrices.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Early applications include computing greatest common divisors of integers and polynomials.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Nowadays, they can be found in NPUs and hardware accelerators based on spatial designs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The parallel input data flows through a network of hard-wired processor nodes, which combine, process, merge or sort the input data into a derived result.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Because the wave-like propagation of data through a systolic array resembles the pulse of the human circulatory system, the name *systolic* was coined from medical terminology.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The name is derived from systole as an analogy to the regular pumping of blood by the heart.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Systolic arrays are often hard-wired for specific operations, such as multiply and accumulate, to perform massively parallel integration, convolution, correlation, matrix multiplication or data sorting tasks.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] They are also used for dynamic programming algorithms, used in DNA and protein sequence analysis.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] A systolic array typically consists of a large monolithic network of primitive computing nodes which can be hardwired or software configured for a specific application.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The nodes are usually fixed and identical, while the interconnect is programmable.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The more general **wavefront** processors, by contrast, employ sophisticated and individually programmable nodes which may or may not be monolithic, depending on the array size and design parameters.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The other distinction is that systolic arrays rely on synchronous data transfers, while wavefront tend to work asynchronously.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The actual processing within each node may be hard wired or block micro coded, in which case the common node personality can be block programmable.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The systolic array paradigm with data-streams driven by data counters, is the counterpart of the Von Neumann architecture with instruction-stream driven by a program counter.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Because a systolic array usually sends and receives multiple data streams, and multiple data counters are needed to generate these data streams, it supports data parallelism.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] A major benefit of systolic arrays is that all operand data and partial results are stored within (passing through) the processor array.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] There is no need to access external buses, main memory or internal caches during each operation as is the case with Von Neumann or Harvard sequential machines.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The sequential limits on parallel performance dictated by Amdahl's Law also do not apply in the same way, because data dependencies are implicitly handled by the programmable node interconnect and there are no sequential steps in managing the highly parallel data flow.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Systolic arrays are therefore extremely good at artificial intelligence, image processing, pattern recognition, computer vision and other tasks that animal brains do particularly well.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Wavefront processors in general can also be very good at machine learning by implementing self configuring neural nets in hardware.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] While systolic arrays are officially classified as MISD, their classification is somewhat problematic.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Because the input is typically a vector of independent values, the systolic array is definitely not SISD.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Since these input values are merged and combined into the result(s) and do not maintain their independence as they would in a SIMD vector processing unit, the array cannot be classified as such.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Consequently, the array cannot be classified as a MIMD either, because MIMD can be viewed as a mere collection of smaller SISD and SIMD machines.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Finally, because the data swarm is transformed as it passes through the array from node to node, the multiple nodes are not operating on the same data, which makes the MISD classification a misnomer.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The other reason why a systolic array should not qualify as a **MISD** is the same as the one which disqualifies it from the SISD category: The input data is typically a vector not a **s**ingle **d**ata value, although one could argue that any given input vector is a single item of data.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] In spite of all of the above, systolic arrays are often offered as a classic example of MISD architecture in textbooks on parallel computing and in engineering classes.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] If the array is viewed from the outside as atomic it should perhaps be classified as **SFMuDMeR** = single function, multiple data, merged result(s).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Systolic arrays use a pre-defined computational flow graph that connects their nodes.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Kahn process networks use a similar flow graph, but are distinguished by the nodes working in lock-step in the systolic array: in a Kahn network, there are FIFO queues between each node.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] A systolic array is composed of matrix-like rows of data processing units called cells.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Data processing units (DPUs) are similar to central processing units (CPUs), (except for the usual lack of a program counter, since operation is transport-triggered, i.e., by the arrival of a data object).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Each cell shares the information with its neighbors immediately after processing.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The systolic array is often rectangular where data flows across the array between neighbour DPUs, often with different data flowing in different directions.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The data streams entering and leaving the ports of the array are generated by auto-sequencing memory units, ASMs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] In embedded systems a data stream may also be input from and/or output to an external source.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] In the example, the green matrix is pre-loaded in the array and can be reused for subsequent multiplications.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] An example of a systolic algorithm might be designed for matrix multiplication.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] One matrix is fed in a row at a time from the top of the array and is passed down the array, the other matrix is fed in a column at a time from the left hand side of the array and passes from left to right.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Dummy values are then passed in until each processor has seen one whole row and one whole column.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] At this point, the result of the multiplication is stored in the array and can now be output a row or a column at a time, flowing down or across the array.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Systolic arrays are arrays of DPUs which are connected to a small number of nearest neighbour DPUs in a mesh-like topology.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] DPUs perform a sequence of operations on data that flows between them.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Because the traditional systolic array synthesis methods have been practiced by algebraic algorithms, only uniform arrays with only linear pipes can be obtained, so that the architectures are the same in all DPUs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The consequence is that only applications with regular data dependencies can be implemented on classical systolic arrays.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Like SIMD machines, clocked systolic arrays compute in "lock-step" with each processor undertaking alternate compute | communicate phases.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] But systolic arrays with asynchronous handshake between DPUs are called *wavefront arrays*.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] One well-known systolic array is Carnegie Mellon University's iWarp processor, which has been manufactured by Intel.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] An iWarp system has a linear array processor connected by data buses going in both directions.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Systolic arrays (also known as *wavefront processors*), were first described by H.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Leiserson, who published the first paper describing systolic arrays in 1979.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] However, the first machine known to have used a similar technique was the Colossus Mark II in 1944.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Colossus used parallel shift registers to pulse data, which is functionally similar to a systolic array, but it lacked the interconnected "processing elements" (PEs) that define the 1978 Kung-Leiserson architecture.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The first machine to be explicitly designed as a systolic array was the WARP computer in 1984.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] A linear systolic array in which the processors are arranged in pairs: one multiplies its input by x and passes the result to the right, the next adds $a_{j}$ and passes the result to the right.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Consider a chain of processing elements (PEs), each performing a multiply-accumulate operation.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] It processes input data ( $x_{i}$ ) and weights ( $w_{i}$ ) systolically, meaning data flows through the array in a regular, rhythmic manner.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The weights remain stationary within each PE, while the input data and partial sums ( $y_{i}$ ) move in opposite directions.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Similarly, n-dimensional convolution can be computed by an n-dimensional array of PEs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Many other implementations of the 1D convolutions are available, with different data flows.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] See Figure 12 for an algorithm that performs on-the-fly least-squares using one- and two-dimensional systolic arrays.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Bubble sort is also an example of 1D systolic computation, although it applies N-1 passes for an array of size N.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Each pass systolically moves the maximum element of a subsequence towards its final location in the sorted result.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] And after all the elements are pushed in, the process is reversed with the minimum element in each PE being popped out (or "pushed up"), resulting in the stream of elements coming out sorted in ascending order.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] Sorting input arrays of larger size (N > P) than the number of processing elements (P) is somewhat complex to do efficiently with such a system, but can be realized (by adding an external serial processor) in O(N log N/log P) time.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/systolic-array] The serial processor needs to manage a "bucket B-tree", where each node in the B-tree has P "buckets" that are eventually each sorted in O(P) time using the PEs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Compared to a graphics processing unit, TPUs are designed for a high volume of low precision computation (e.g. as little as 8-bit precision) with more input/output operations per joule, without hardware for rasterisation or texture mapping.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The TPU ASICs are mounted in a heatsink assembly, which can fit in a hard drive slot within a data center rack, according to Norman Jouppi.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Different types of processors are suited for different types of machine learning models.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] TPUs are well suited for convolutional neural networks (CNNs), while GPUs have benefits for some fully connected neural networks, and CPUs can have advantages for recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In 2013, Google recruited Amir Salek to establish custom silicon development capabilities for the company's datacenters.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] According to Jonathan Ross, one of the original TPU engineers, and later the founder of Groq, three separate groups at Google were developing AI accelerators, with the TPU, a systolic array, being the design that was ultimately selected.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Jouppi served as the tech lead and principal architect for Google's Tensor Processing Unit development, leading the rapid design, verification, and deployment of the first TPU to production in just 15 months.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The tensor processing unit was announced in May 2016 at the Google I/O conference, when the company said that the TPU had been used inside their data centers for over a year.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google's 2017 paper describing its creation cites previous systolic matrix multipliers of similar architecture built in the 1990s.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The chip was specifically designed for Google's TensorFlow framework, a symbolic math library used for machine learning applications such as neural networks.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] However, as of 2017 Google still used CPUs and GPUs for other types of machine learning.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Other AI accelerator designs are appearing from other vendors also and are aimed at embedded and robotics markets.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google has also used TPUs for Google Street View text processing and was able to find all the text in the Street View database in less than five days.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In Google Photos, an individual TPU can process over 100 million photos a day.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It is also used in RankBrain which Google uses to provide search results.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google provides third parties access to TPUs through its *Cloud TPU* service as part of the Google Cloud Platform and through its notebook-based services Kaggle and Colaboratory.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Broadcom is a co-developer of TPUs, translating Google's architecture and specifications into manufacturable silicon.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It provides proprietary technologies such as SerDes high-speed interfaces, overseeing ASIC design, and managing chip fabrication and packaging through third-party foundries like Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC), covering all generations since the program's inception.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In September 2025, Google is in talks with several "neoclouds," including Crusoe and CoreWeave, about deploying TPU in their datacenter.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In November 2025, Meta is in talks with Google to deploy TPUs in its AI datacenters.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The first-generation TPU is an 8-bit matrix multiplication engine, driven with CISC instructions by the host processor across a PCIe 3.0 bus.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It is manufactured on a 28 nm process with a die size ≤ 331 mm2.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The clock speed is 700 MHz and it has a thermal design power of 28–40 W.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It has 28 MiB of on chip memory, and 4 MiB of 32-bit accumulators taking the results of a 256×256 systolic array of 8-bit multipliers.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Within the TPU package is 8 GiB of dual-channel 2133 MHz DDR3 SDRAM offering 34 GB/s of bandwidth.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Instructions transfer data to or from the host, perform matrix multiplications or convolutions, and apply activation functions.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The second-generation TPU was announced in May 2017.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google stated the first-generation TPU design was limited by memory bandwidth and using 16 GB of High Bandwidth Memory in the second-generation design increased bandwidth to 600 GB/s and performance to 45 teraFLOPS.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The TPUs are then arranged into four-chip modules with a performance of 180 teraFLOPS.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Then 64 of these modules are assembled into 256-chip pods with 11.5 petaFLOPS of performance.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Notably, while the first-generation TPUs were limited to integers, the second-generation TPUs can also calculate in floating point, introducing the bfloat16 format invented by Google Brain.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] This makes the second-generation TPUs useful for both training and inference of machine learning models.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google has stated these second-generation TPUs will be available on the Google Compute Engine for use in TensorFlow applications.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The third-generation TPU was announced on May 8, 2018.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google announced that processors themselves are twice as powerful as the second-generation TPUs, and would be deployed in pods with four times as many chips as the preceding generation.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] This results in an 8-fold increase in performance per pod (with up to 1,024 chips per pod) compared to the second-generation TPU deployment.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] On May 18, 2021, Google CEO Sundar Pichai spoke about TPU v4 Tensor Processing Units during his keynote at the Google I/O virtual conference.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] TPU v4 improved performance by more than 2x over TPU v3 chips.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Pichai said "A single v4 pod contains 4,096 v4 chips, and each pod has 10x the interconnect bandwidth per chip at scale, compared to any other networking technology.” An April 2023 paper by Google claims TPU v4 is 5–87% faster than a Nvidia A100 at machine learning benchmarks.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] There is also an "inference" version, called v4i, that does not require liquid cooling.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In 2021, Google revealed the physical layout of TPU v5 is being designed with the assistance of a novel application of deep reinforcement learning.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google claims TPU v5 is nearly twice as fast as TPU v4, and based on that and the relative performance of TPU v4 over A100, some speculate TPU v5 as being as fast as or faster than an H100.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Similar to the v4i being a lighter-weight version of the v4, the fifth generation has a "cost-efficient" version called v5e.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In December 2023, Google announced TPU v5p which is claimed to be competitive with the Nvidia H100.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In May 2024, at the Google I/O conference, Google announced Trillium, which became available in preview in October 2024.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google claimed a 4.7 times performance increase relative to TPU v5e, via larger matrix multiplication units and an increased clock speed.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] High bandwidth memory (HBM) capacity and bandwidth have also doubled.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] A pod can contain up to 256 Trillium units.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In April 2025, at Google Cloud Next conference, Google unveiled TPU v7.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] This new chip, called Ironwood, will come in two configurations: a 256-chip cluster and a 9,216-chip cluster.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Ironwood will have a peak computational performance rate of 4,614 TFLOP/s.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] On April 22, 2026, Google announced the eighth generation of its Tensor Processing Units, consisting of two specialized chips: the **TPU 8t** and the **TPU 8i**.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] This marks the first time Google has bifurcated its TPU architecture into separate training and inference-optimized designs.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Both chips are hosted on Google's custom Arm-based **Axion** CPUs and utilize 4th-generation liquid cooling.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The TPU 8t ("Training") is optimized for large-scale pre-training of frontier models and embedding-heavy workloads.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It delivers 12.6 FP4 PFLOPs of peak performance and features 216 GB of HBM3e memory with 6,528 GB/s bandwidth.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It uses the Virgo Network fabric, allowing it to scale up to 9,600 chips per "superpod," delivering 121 FP4 ExaFLOPs of compute performance.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The TPU 8i ("Inference") is designed for high-speed serving, AI agents, and long-context reasoning.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It delivers 10.1 FP4 PFLOPs of peak performance and features 288 GB of HBM3e memory with 8,601 GB/s bandwidth.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] It includes 384 MB of on-chip SRAM, a three-fold increase over the previous generation.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The TPU 8i introduces a "Boardfly" network topology and a Collectives Acceleration Engine (CAE) which reduces synchronization latency by five times.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In July 2018, Google announced the Edge TPU.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The Edge TPU is Google's purpose-built ASIC chip designed to run machine learning (ML) models for edge computing, meaning it is much smaller and consumes far less power compared to the TPUs hosted in Google datacenters (also known as Cloud TPUs).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In January 2019, Google made the Edge TPU available to developers with a line of products under the Coral brand.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The Edge TPU is capable of 4 trillion operations per second with 2 W of electrical power.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The product offerings include a single-board computer (SBC), a system on module (SoM), a USB accessory, a mini PCI-e card, and an M.2 card.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The SBC Coral Dev Board and Coral SoM both run Mendel Linux OS – a derivative of Debian.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The USB, PCI-e, and M.2 products function as add-ons to existing computer systems, and support Debian-based Linux systems on x86-64 and ARM64 hosts (including Raspberry Pi).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The machine learning runtime used to execute models on the Edge TPU is based on TensorFlow Lite.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The Edge TPU is only capable of accelerating forward-pass operations, which means it's primarily useful for performing inferences (although it is possible to perform lightweight transfer learning on the Edge TPU).
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The Edge TPU also only supports 8-bit math, meaning that for a network to be compatible with the Edge TPU, it needs to either be trained using the TensorFlow quantization-aware training technique, or since late 2019 it's also possible to use post-training quantization.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] On November 12, 2019, Asus announced a pair of single-board computer (SBCs) featuring the Edge TPU.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The Asus Tinker Edge T and Tinker Edge R Board designed for IoT and edge AI.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The SBCs officially support Android and Debian operating systems.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] ASUS has also demonstrated a mini PC called Asus PN60T featuring the Edge TPU.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] On January 2, 2020, Google announced the Coral Accelerator Module and Coral Dev Board Mini, to be demonstrated at CES 2020 later the same month.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The Coral Accelerator Module is a multi-chip module featuring the Edge TPU, PCIe and USB interfaces for easier integration.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] The Coral Dev Board Mini is a smaller single-board computer (SBC) featuring the Coral Accelerator Module and MediaTek 8167s SoC.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] On October 15, 2019, Google announced the Pixel 4 smartphone, which contains an Edge TPU called the Pixel Neural Core.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google described it as "customized to meet the requirements of key camera features in Pixel 4", using a neural network search that sacrifices some accuracy in favor of minimizing latency and power use.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Google followed the Pixel Neural Core by integrating an Edge TPU into a custom system-on-chip named Google Tensor, which was released in 2021 with the Pixel 6 line of smartphones.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In 2019, Singular Computing, founded in 2009 by Joseph Bates, a visiting professor at MIT, filed suit against Google alleging patent infringement in TPU chips.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] In a 2023 court filing, Singular Computing specifically called out Google's use of bfloat16, as that exceeds the dynamic range of float16.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Singular Computing claims non-standard floating point formats were non-obvious in 2009, but Google retorts that the VFLOAT format, with a configurable number of exponent bits, existed as prior art in 2002.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] By January 2024, subsequent lawsuits by Singular Computing had brought the number of patents being litigated up to eight.
[src:tensor-processing-unit/tensor-processing-unit] Towards the end of the trial later that month, Google agreed to a settlement with undisclosed terms.
